english:
  title: On the Ancestral Rites of Officials and Scholars
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In ancient times, the Son of Heaven maintained seven ancestral temples. The founding king, upon receiving the Mandate of Heaven, became the Great Progenitor, whose temple stood at the center. To the east were three shrines of the Zhao lineage, to the west three of the Mu lineage—six temples in all. The two southern temples, east and west, honored the father and grandfather. The two central temples, east and west, honored the great-grandfather and great-great-grandfather. These four comprised the temples of the four closest generations. The two northern temples, east and west, honored the father and grandfather of the great-grandfather, forming the two distant shrines. Together, the four close temples and two distant shrines formed the three Zhao and three Mu. When a king of exceptional virtue and merit passed beyond the four generations and his temple would be dismantled, a separate shrine was established north of the northern Mu temple, called the Eternal Shrine, preserved for a hundred generations like the Great Progenitor. The Zhou's Temple of King Wen and Temple of King Wu exemplify this. Including the Great Progenitor, two Eternal Shrines, three Zhao, and three Mu, this made nine temples—the system of the Son of Heaven.

    For feudal lords, the founding prince became the Great Temple, with the great-grandfather, great-great-grandfather, grandfather, and father as the four close temples—called two Zhao and two Mu. There were no distant shrines, nor separate Eternal Shrines for merit. Thus their grand seasonal gatherings brought together the two Zhao and two Mu, but not all dissolved temples. Only when conducting the Great Gathering could all destroyed temples merge with the Great Progenitor's shrine.

    For great officers, three temples existed: the founder held the central position as the Great Temple, with one Zhao and one Mu representing grandfather and father. For upper scholars, two temples sufficed—only grandfather and father, without a Great Temple. For middle and lower scholars, but one temple remained—the father's alone, lacking the grandfather's. Commoners had no temples, making offerings to their father in the ancestral chamber.

    When middle and lower scholars performed regular rites, they could only honor the father. To honor the grandfather, they did so at the father's temple. Upper scholars honored great-grandfather and great-great-grandfather at the grandfather's temple. Great officers performed rites to all ancestors at the Great Temple.

    In ancient practice, only the Son of Heaven and feudal lords possessed spirit tablets. Great officers and scholars had none, merely arranging seats to receive the spirits. Yi Chuan's ritual system granted spirit tablets to all officials and scholars, allowing them to honor four generations back to the great-grandfather—presuming the rites of feudal lords. Further, his system of winter solstice offerings to the primordial ancestor and spring offerings to the ancestral line mimicked the Son of Heaven's grand ritual gatherings. Thus Zhu Xi initially followed Yi Chuan's rites, performing these two observances, but later recognizing their presumption, he ceased them.

    In these latter times without feudalism, we must balance ancient and modern propriety. Officials of the third rank and above may follow the old feudal custom, honoring four generations, yet lacking enfeoffed territories, should possess no spirit tablets. Those of the sixth rank follow great officers' rites; seventh rank follows upper scholars; eighth and ninth ranks follow middle and lower scholars—thus approaching rightness.

    When Zhu Xi speaks of "two tablets," he means the successor bearing the tablets of both father and mother. When he says "two tablets mutually support each other, so the spirit remains undivided," he means the parents' spirits continuously dwell with the tablets, requiring no separate spirit plaques. When he says the gathering "extends to the great-grandfather," he means reaching upward from below. Though the great-grandfather traditionally had no temple, if he earned merit for the state and received the ruler's favor, four generations could gather in his honor—great officers at their Great Temple, upper scholars at their grandfather's temple, middle and lower scholars at their father's temple.

    The foregoing presents only the essentials, not exhaustive detail. Some argue: "Ritual adapts to the age, gaining and losing as time demands. That great officers and scholars possess spirit tablets began with Yi Chuan's system and causes no harm to propriety. Yet where temples exist, tablets should too; where none exist, tablets rest in the tomb. For ancestral offerings, arrange seats in the temple with tablets, worshiping at those shrines." Since present temple systems scarcely follow the ancient way, we should adopt Yi Chuan's established rites.
  footnotes:
    - Yi Chuan (伊川) refers to Cheng Yi, the Northern Song Neo-Confucian philosopher whose ritual reforms expanded ancestral veneration rights to lower-ranking officials and scholars.
    - The Zhao (昭) and Mu (穆) lineages represent the alternating male descent lines—one moving forward, one moving backward through generations in temple arrangement.
    - Zhu Xi (朱子), the great Song Neo-Confucian synthesizer, initially adopted Yi Chuan's reforms but later modified them, seeking to balance practical accommodation with classical propriety.
    - Spirit tablets (神主) were inscribed wooden tablets believed to house the ancestor's spirit and served as the focus of ritual veneration.
